<HEADLINE>
<P>
PROPOSITIONS 136, 137 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I am questioning the legality of Prop. 136. How can a measure that can pass 
with as little as 50% plus one vote require a 66.7% vote to overturn it? Since 
Prop. 13 passed, there have been many measures to raise money that received a 
far greater percentage than Prop. 13 but fell short of two-thirds and thus were 
defeated. 
</P>
<P>
Is that right? 
</P>
<P>
If Prop. 136 passes and is not struck down as unconstitutional, we'll probably 
see every future proposition with the same two-thirds clause. Try to imagine 
the chaos the initiative process would be dealing with. 
</P>
<P>
MICHAEL LORRAINE, Simi Valley 
</P>
</TEXT>
