<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
VIRGINIA; 
</P>
<P>
REMAINS OF 2 MISSING SOLDIERS LAID TO REST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The remains of two American soldiers killed in the last major assault of the 
Vietnam War were laid to rest at Arlington National Cemetery, 19 years after 
their helicopter was shot down. Vietnam veterans hailed the return of the 
remains to the United States in July as the result of the first joint 
U.S.-Laotian search for Americans missing in action. Capt. Keith A. Brandt of 
Bellingham, Wash., and Lt. Alan B. Boffman of Norfolk, Va., crashed March 18, 
1971, while attempting to save 88 South Vietnamese infantrymen stranded in a 
thrust into Laos. 
</P>
