<HEADLINE>
<P>
DESCRIPTION IS RELEASED OF NEWBORN FOUND DEAD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAVAN MAHARAJ, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SANTA ANA 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A newborn boy found dead in a commercial trash bin in Laguna Hills on Thursday 
was a Caucasian with blond hair and blue eyes, authorities said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
"We're saying that the baby was born (a healthy child) between midnight and 8 
a.m. on Wednesday," said Lt. Robert Rivas, a sheriff's spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
"He was dead for about a day (before he was found)." 
</P>
<P>
Orange County coroner's officials performed an autopsy Friday on the infant, 
who was found by a man who frequently picks through the dumpsters at the 
Saddleback Business Complex just off Interstate 5 below the upscale homes of 
Nellie Gail Ranch. 
</P>
<P>
The man, who was not identified, called sheriff's investigators, who retrieved 
the body from the trash bin. Witnesses said the child was wrapped in a white 
cloth and partially covered by debris. 
</P>
<P>
Rivas declined to reveal the cause of death, saying that the release of that 
information could affect the homicide investigation. 
</P>
<P>
He said that while homicide was a possible cause of death, the baby could have 
died from overexposure. 
</P>
<P>
"We're not ruling anything out," Rivas said. "We are handling it as a possible 
homicide. But it could be natural causes; it could be accidental manslaughter 
or homicide. We handle it to the extreme to make sure we cover all bases." 
</P>
<P>
Rivas said investigators have few leads and are seeking the public's 
assistance. 
</P>
<P>
"We need help," he said, adding that the baby's mother has not been identified. 
Rivas said that she may be seeking medical attention for possible hemorrhaging. 
</P>
<P>
"We need any leads we can get," he said. "We are stressing the urgency." 
</P>
<P>
Anyone with information should call detectives Rudy Garcia or Tim Carney at 
(714) 647-7000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
