<HEADLINE>
<P>
OWNERS OFFER TO CLEAR CHATSWORTH SITE TO REDUCE COURTHOUSE COST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By AMY LOUISE KAZMIN, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The owners of a defunct power-tool manufacturing company, who want to sell the 
Chatsworth property to the county for a municipal courthouse site, have offered 
to demolish the vacant buildings to reduce the cost of a county purchase. 
</P>
<P>
Stephen Farley, executive vice president of Allegretti and Co., said he 
submitted a proposal to county court administrators last week offering to 
absorb the cost of clearing several warehouses from the nine-acre parcel at 
9200 Mason Ave. as part of the sales agreement. 
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the county, Farley offered to sell the cleared land for $12 
million to $14 million, a price he said was "very competitive." 
</P>
<P>
Farley said he has not received a response. A court spokeswoman confirmed 
Friday that the offer was received, but declined to comment on its status. 
</P>
<P>
Court officials, who have entered into negotiations with a developer to 
purchase another Chatsworth site for the new West Valley municipal courthouse, 
earlier rejected the Allegretti property as too expensive. 
</P>
<P>
However, Farley said Friday he believed the county overestimated the cost of 
demolishing the old buildings on his property. 
</P>
<P>
In their initial reports, Farley said, county officials estimated that it would 
cost $2.8 million to clear the land. Farley said he obtained estimates from 
demolition firms stating the site could be cleared for about $280,000. 
</P>
<P>
Last month, Farley complained that his land had not been given fair 
consideration before county officials decided to open negotiations with 
developer Alexander Haagen for a nine-acre parcel at Plummer Street and 
Winnetka Avenue. 
</P>
<P>
The Plummer Street proposal has raised vehement protests from nearby homeowners 
who fear that the courthouse will generate traffic congestion and graffiti, 
increase crime and reduce property values. 
</P>
<P>
In response to Farley's complaint and to the growing pressure from homeowners 
to find an alternative site, County Supervisor Mike Antonovich requested that 
court officials reconsider the Allegretti site while continuing to negotiate 
with Haagen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
